1. Description: This query returns one row per product showing the number of days it was out of stock over a period. This measures how frequently each product experienced stockouts. The source databases do not store daily stock states, so it cannot determine how many days a product had zero inventory in the past. 
SELECT p.ProductName, COUNT(*) AS DaysOutOfStock 
FROM FactInventory fi 
JOIN ProductDim p ON fi.ProductKey = p.ProductKey 
WHERE fi.CurrentStock = 0 
GROUP BY p.ProductName; 

2. Description: This returns one row per calendar date showing the total stock across all products and branches on that day. It sums the CurrentStock values from FactInventory and groups them by date using DatetimeDim. The output is a time series of overall inventory levels. The source only stores current stock and stock logs. To get stock for each past day, you would need to reconstruct it by replaying all log changes, which is complex and unreliable 
SELECT d.FullDate, SUM(fi.CurrentStock) AS TotalStock 
FROM FactInventory fi 
JOIN DatetimeDim d ON fi.DateKey = d.DateKey 
GROUP BY d.FullDate 
ORDER BY d.FullDate; 

3. Description: Calculates the total lifetime spend of customers by summing the revenue from the FactSales table and grouping the original SourceCustomerID from the CustomerDim table, aggregating all purchases made by a single person. This query is used to identify the top 5 highest-value customers. 
SELECT 
    c.SourceCustomerID, 
    c.CustomerName, 
    SUM(f.Revenue) AS TotalLifetimeSpend 
FROM FactSales f 
JOIN CustomerDim c ON f.CustomerKey = c.CustomerKey 
GROUP BY c.SourceCustomerID, c.CustomerName 
ORDER BY TotalLifetimeSpend DESC 
LIMIT 5; 

4. Description: Aggregates the total revenue and the count of distinct orders from the FactSales table, grouped by the year and quarter from the DatetimeDim table. This query assesses quarterly business performance and sales trends. Because the source databases are isolated by their geographic locations, this query cannot run on the source databases, as it requires the centralized warehouse. 
SELECT 
    d.Year, 
    d.Quarter, 
    SUM(f.Revenue) AS QuarterlyRevenue, 
    COUNT(DISTINCT f.SourceOrderID) AS NumberOfOrders 
FROM FactSales f 
JOIN DatetimeDim d ON f.DateKey = d.DateKey 
GROUP BY d.Year, d.Quarter 
ORDER BY d.Year, d.Quarter; 

5. Description: Identifies distinct products from the ProductDim table that exist in the FactInventory table but do not have any sales records in the FactSales table. This query is used to find stagnant inventory, showing products that have never been sold. 
SELECT DISTINCT 
    p.ProductName 
FROM ProductDim p 
JOIN FactInventory i ON p.ProductKey = i.ProductKey 
WHERE p.ProductKey NOT IN ( 
    SELECT ProductKey FROM FactSales 
); 

6. Description: Uses a window function to rank product categories based on their total generated revenue, partitioned by the year and month from the DatetimeDim table. It then filters the subquery to only return the category with a rank of 1. This query is used to determine the most profitable product category for every month.  
SELECT * 
FROM ( 
    SELECT 
        d.Month, 
        d.Year, 
        p.Category, 
        SUM(f.Revenue) AS Revenue, 
        RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY d.Year, d.Month ORDER BY SUM(f.Revenue) DESC) AS SalesRank 
    FROM FactSales f 
    JOIN ProductDim p ON f.ProductKey = p.ProductKey 
    JOIN DatetimeDim d ON f.DateKey = d.DateKey 
    GROUP BY d.Year, d.Month, p.Category 
) AS RankedSales 
WHERE SalesRank = 1; 

7. Description: This query scans the history of the warehouse to find items that have been sold at multiple different prices over time, displaying the lowest and highest historical selling prices. This is used to track the pricing history of frequently updated products. 
SELECT * 
P.ProductName, P.Category,  
COUNT(DISTINCT FS.UnitPrice) AS UniquePricePointsSold, 
MIN(FS.UnitPrice) AS LowestHistoricalPrice,  
MAX(FS.UnitPrice) AS HighestHistoricalPrice 
FROM FactSales FS  
JOIN ProductDim P ON FS.ProductKey = P.ProductKey  
GROUP BY P.ProductName, P.Category  
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT FS.UnitPrice) > 1  
ORDER BY UniquePricePointsSold DESC; 

8. Description: Retrieves the branch key, city, product details, current stock, and restock threshold by joining FactInventory, BranchDim, and ProductDim. It filters inventory records where the current stock level is below the restock threshold. This query is used to monitor inventory snapshots to identify locations needing restocking.  
SELECT 
    b.BranchKey, 
    b.City, 
    p.ProductKey, 
    p.ProductName, 
    i.CurrentStock, 
    i.RestockThreshold 
FROM FactInventory i 
JOIN BranchDim b ON i.BranchKey = b.BranchKey 
JOIN ProductDim p ON i.ProductKey = p.ProductKey 
WHERE i.CurrentStock < i.RestockThreshold 
ORDER BY b.BranchKey, i.CurrentStock ASC; 

9. Description: Calculates the average order value by dividing the total revenue by the count of distinct source order IDs. It joins the FactSales table with the BranchDim table to group and displays the results by specific branch location. This query evaluates the average transaction size at different branches. 
SELECT 
    f.BranchKey, 
    b.City, 
    SUM(f.Revenue) / COUNT(DISTINCT f.SourceOrderID) AS AvgOrderValue 
FROM FactSales f 
JOIN BranchDim b ON f.BranchKey = b.BranchKey 
GROUP BY f.BranchKey, b.City; 
